This is a spontaneous report from a contactable health care professional received by Pfizer from My/Ian 
(manufacturer control number 2013-EPI-00174), license party for Epinephrine (EpiPen). 
An 8-year-old Caucasian male who initially complained of a "hot" mouth and stomachache 5 minutes after ingesting 
jelly beans, lemonade, and potato chips at a school party. No rash or other visible symptoms accompanied his 
reaction, Thirty minutes post ingestion, he complained of worsening abdominal pain, a ''fuzzy" feeling in this throat, 
and chest pain. He was sent to the nurse's office, where he was evaluated but no medications were given. His 
mother was called, and he was driven to his pediatrician's office. On presentation to the pediatric office, now about 
60 minutes after ingesting the foods at the school party, the patient complained of tightness in his throat and chest 
and severe abdominal pain. Epinephrine, diphenhydramine, albuterol, and oxygen were administered, and 911 was 
called. He responded briefly but then became hypotensive and cyanotic and was transported to the emergency 
